2500|$|Lawrence tapped 32-year-old Herbert York, {{a former}} {{graduate}} student of his, to run Livermore. Under York, the Lab had four main programs: Project Sherwood (the <b>Magnetic</b> <b>Fusion</b> Program), Project Whitney (the weapons design program), diagnostic weapon experiments (both for the Los Alamos and Livermore laboratories), and a basic physics program. York {{and the new}} lab embraced the Lawrence [...] "big science" [...] approach, tackling challenging projects with physicists, chemists, engineers, and computational scientists working together in multidisciplinary teams. Lawrence died in August 1958 and shortly after, the university's board of regents named both laboratories for him, as the Lawrence Radiation Laboratory.|$|E
